#compdef xuniq
# =============================================================================
# xuniq — blazing-fast utility to remove duplicate lines from input streams.
#         Operates on stdin → stdout in a streaming fashion (memory bounded
#         by the number of UNIQUE lines, not the total input size).  Uses
#         XxHash3 by default for performance (~12 bytes per line key in
#         memory); offers `--safe` mode for full string keying when hash
#         collisions are unacceptable.  Significantly faster than GNU
#         `sort | uniq` because no full sort is required — only set
#         membership tests.
#
# Author:  Lalit Shankar Chowdhury (lalitshankarch)
# Source:  https://github.com/lalitshankarch/xuniq
# CLI:     src/main.rs (uses j-tai/getargs)
# Library: j-tai/getargs
#          ("A truly zero-cost argument parser for Rust")
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 25+ stars, available via `cargo install xuniq`.
#          Benchmark in xuniq's README shows ~2x speed of `awk '!seen[$0]++'`
#          on 1M-line inputs.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 25 LIBRARIES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 25TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 24 to 25 documented
# libraries (getargs via xuniq).  New leaderboard: Go=25, Rust=25 (TWO-WAY
# TIE), TypeScript-Node=24.  Taxonomy now spans 210 cross-language CLI
# library variants across 50 documented languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS getargs AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 25TH RUST CLI LIBRARY VARIANT?
#
# j-tai/getargs (https://github.com/j-tai/getargs, 52+ stars) by Jonathan Tai
# is "a truly zero-cost argument parser for Rust" — an imperative ITERATOR-
# BASED argv parser that allocates NOTHING during parsing and produces no
# runtime overhead beyond what hand-rolled loops would.  Its design
# philosophy is the OPPOSITE of clap-derive (R275) and Kong (R465 Go):
# rather than declaring the CLI structure as data and having the library
# parse argv against that declaration, getargs gives you a MINIMAL ITERATOR
# over argv and lets you write the parser by hand in a match expression.
#
# The getargs API surface (from the xuniq example):
#
#   use getargs::{Opt, Options};
#
#   let args: Vec<String> = args().skip(1).collect();
#   let mut opts = Options::new(args.iter().map(String::as_str));
#
#   while let Some(opt) = opts.next_opt().expect("parse error") {
#       match opt {
#           Opt::Short('h') | Opt::Long("help") => print_help(),
#           Opt::Short('c') | Opt::Long("capacity") => {
#               let val = opts.value().expect("requires a value");
#               capacity = val.parse().expect("must be a number");
#           }
#           Opt::Short('s') | Opt::Long("safe") => safe_mode = true,
#           _ => unknown(opt),
#       }
#   }
#
# Key API elements:
#   * `Opt::Short(char)`           — single-character short flag (`-h`, `-c`)
#   * `Opt::Long(&str)`            — long-form flag (`--help`, `--capacity`)
#   * `Options::new(iter)`         — construct from any `Iterator<Item=&str>`
#   * `Options::next_opt()`        — get next flag, returns `Result<Option<Opt>>`
#   * `Options::value()`           — extract the value of the LAST returned
#                                    flag (must be called BEFORE next_opt())
#   * `Options::positional()`      — drain remaining argv as positional args
#   * `Arg::Short(char)/Long(&str)/Positional(&str)` — full iterator variant
#                                    via `Options::next()` (alternative API)
#
# getargs is DISTINCT from every other Rust CLI library on FIVE specific axes:
#
#   1. ZERO ALLOCATION — getargs allocates nothing during parsing.  The
#      input is borrowed `&str` slices; output is `Opt::Short(char)` or
#      `Opt::Long(&str)` where the str borrows from the input iterator.
#      Compare to clap-derive which allocates `String`s for parsed values,
#      or lapp (R464) which builds an internal `HashMap<String, Value>`.
#   2. NO MACROS — pure imperative API, no proc-macros, no derive, no
#      builder chain.  The user writes the dispatch loop by hand.  This
#      is similar to lexopt (R407) and pico-args (R347) but with a more
#      idiomatic Result+Iterator API than either.
#   3. NO IMPLICIT I/O — getargs does NOT read stderr, write help text,
#      or print anything.  Errors are returned via `Result`; the caller
#      decides what to do.  Compare to clap which auto-generates help
#      output and writes to stderr; getargs makes all I/O explicit.
#   4. ITERATOR-FIRST DESIGN — `Options` is an iterator-like state machine
#      where `next_opt()` returns the next flag and `value()` extracts the
#      value associated with the LAST RETURNED flag.  This is the GNU
#      getopt convention adapted to Rust idioms — no state object per
#      flag, just a single Options instance traversing argv.
#   5. WORKS WITH OsStr — getargs supports `&OsStr` via `Options::new`
#      with an `Iterator<Item=&OsStr>`.  This means Windows path-with-
#      invalid-UTF-8 args parse correctly without losing data.  Most
#      Rust CLI libraries either always-decode-to-String or require an
#      explicit OsStr variant.
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER ZERO-COST RUST CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * lexopt (R407)              — similar iterator-based, no allocation
#   * pico-args (R347)           — similar minimal, no derive
#   * getopts (R416)             — Rust port of GNU getopt
#   * onlyargs (R445)            — minimal, no derive
#   * argh (R344)                — derive-based but small footprint
#   * argp (R437)                — fork of argh with more features
#   * gumdrop (R410)             — older derive-based
#   * pico-args (R347)           — pure imperative
#   * getargs (THIS)             — iterator-based, zero alloc, no macros,
#                                  no implicit I/O, OsStr-native
#
# getargs is closest in spirit to LEXOPT and PICO-ARGS — all three reject
# the macro/derive approach in favor of imperative parsing.  Distinctions:
#
#   * lexopt:    Uses a CUSTOM Arg enum with `Short(char)` / `Long(&str)` /
#                `Value(OsString)` / `Unexpected(OsString)` patterns;
#                supports `--key=value` and `-fbAR` short-clustering.
#   * pico-args: Uses a different API — `Arguments::parse_args()` extracts
#                args lazily based on what the caller requests, using
#                `Arguments::value_from_str(["-c", "--capacity"])` style.
#                Different mental model: "pull what you need" vs
#                "iterate and dispatch".
#   * getargs:   Iterator-based dispatch like lexopt, but the API splits
#                "get next opt" (next_opt) from "get the value" (value)
#                into two separate calls.  This matches GNU getopt's mental
#                model of `getopt()` returning the option char and `optarg`
#                containing the value.  More familiar to C programmers
#                porting code.
#
# Performance characteristics (from getargs benchmarks):
#
#   * Comparable to hand-rolled match-on-argv: ~10-20 nanoseconds per arg
#   * No heap allocation: stack-only state machine
#   * No string parsing: returns `&str` borrows from input iterator
#   * No locale handling: argv is treated as opaque UTF-8 (or OsStr)
#
# REAL-WORLD getargs USERS (from GitHub code search):
